<br>
First of all - I believe very much that we should live as we were intented as much as that is possible. From our teeth, we are most definetly omnivores - hence we eat both plants and animal. I think that alone, is enough justification against forcing people to become vegans.<br>
<br>
The next issue is our moral and ethical responsibility to the rest of the world. Your right, there are millions if not billions of people starving with thousands dying every day. I don't contest it, but I refuse to accept that it is as a direct consequence of western diets. At the present moment, I believe(although I may be wrong) we produce enough food to feed every soul on earth adequately. So why don't we? Logistically we cannot share out the food. It's too difficult getting the food to the people who need it most.<br>
<br>
So why don't they produce it themselves?<br>
<br>
This links to another point which I believe in very strongly. We may claim that with a change to veganism we can feed more people, but I feel that is wrong. I already feel that the human population is placing too much of a burden on the environment and actually believe(its twisted I admit) that poverty,hunger and diseases such as AIDS are trying to keep our population in check. This doesn't mean I want people to die, it means I would rather see the earth reach a sustainable level of population. The population levels we are reaching for (by UN estimates) are utterly unsustainable and will give rise to the host of problems outlined in the article you posted in the second reply.<br>
<br>
In fairness, I totally reject the arguments put forward attributing the way we eat to world poverty. Completely.<br>
<br>
There are other issues of course.<br>
Our Health for instance, I agree has much to do with what and how we eat. Again however I refuse to accept that a vegan diet is better for us then a moderate and balanced meat containing diet. Of course fast food isn't healthy, nor is the british obsession with bacon, sausage and whatever else - but to completely miss out on healthy well prepared meat I feel can do as much harm as good.<br>
The Environment is another issue on which these campaigns focus. Again I must disagree to a major extent. It's not our eating habits that fuel the overproduction of our land - It's goverment policy. Even then - its not only due to this. In the American and Canadian prarie lands, soil erosion is a well known problem. Quite often the simplest cause to blame is just to say its overproduction. But lets look at the British farming scene, which has been going on for centuries longer, and still produces almost three times the average yield that they do in North America. Yet we hear precious little about soil erosion in this country, mainly because its not a problem. We manage and care for the land better because it is more valuable an asset then in other countries, and as a result are able to produce more without putting it at risk. People need to be educated around the world in better farming practices(perhaps organic, perhaps with the help of GM).<br>
<br>
The only industry I would say may benefit from less consumption is the fishing industry. We are dangerously overfishing the seas, and unlike agricultural land - there is no easy way for us to manage and control its quality. There are no quick fixes, and solutions may be dangerous on a global scale due to the turbulous nature of the sea, whereas on land activity will always be restricted to small areas.<br>
<br>
I've written far too much already, but have so much more to say.<br>
<br>
But as you can guess Veganism, isn't for me.<br>
